title: ﻿style Guide
author: Using three @ signs to separate each recipe. I’ll find and replace them with something more permanent later

title: Recipe Title
author: Authors
summary:
If the ingredients are in two or more subsections, list them like so (Tab + ⌘ + Shift + 7)

The ingredients in the book are listed in two columns. Try to format these so that the ingredients in the first column are listed first and then list the ingredients from the second column.

If the Steps are in two or more subsections, list them like so (Tab + ⌘ + Shift + 8)

Any chunks of text containing additional recipe details can be left in the same position as they are originally, just try to remove newline characters if you see them.

Phase 2 Style Guide -

Add a fourth @ before the recipe title when you have applied the formatting

Making ingredients parsable

Amount

# if there is a comma present, split line on “,” and only look at first (zero-ith) substring, else use whole line

If there is a unit (parentheses are present), just grab the substring before the ( and use the strip method to remove whitespace on the ends (this will allow for situations where the amount is not a number - Ex: Few (drops) hot sauce

Empty string if none found

Whole values: 1 (cup)

Compound Fractions: 1 ½ (cups)

Fractions: ½ (cup)

Not present: salt and pepper

Unit

## NOTE: if comma present in line, split line on “,” and only look at first (zero-ith) substring (because additional recipe details may have parentheses)

Surrounded by parentheses: 1 (cup)

Units that are different when Amount is <= 1

(most other units)

Ingredient Name

In this case, the person uploading the recipe will need to manually update the value

Extra Details

Rewrite extra details to be after the ingredient name. Can have additional commas/parentheses, but omit them if they aren’t adding value

Find first comma, if not found, return empty string. else , return second half of line

Corner cases to just use your best judgement on

When the recipe has suggests two different ingredients, the second could be recorded as a note or beside the original. The difference in the end is that the note is a lighter gray https://demo.wprecipemaker.com/chic-recipe-template/

But these cases of alternative ingredients are messy in other recipes, so don’t over think it too much. All in all, we want the info visible clearly on the page, even if it doesn’t properly conform to the variable names that are holding the details.

Let me know if there’s a more preferred way

title: Hot Chocolate
author: Mary Jo McFadden
summary: This Hot Chocolate Recipe was prepared and served by Mary Jo McFadden when she entertained the Brunkhorst/McFadden families at Christmas. This recipe was submitted by several family members with notes attached how each would look forward to this awesome treat each year! (Note: Mary Jo is known for always typing instead of writing. She was also noted for calling her children and siblings in the morning to wish them a "good day!" Mary Jo is sadly missed by all who knew her.)
ingredients: [{'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'cocoa', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'water', 'notes': 'boiling', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': 'qt. heavy cream', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': 'quart', 'name': 'milk', 'notes': 'scalding hot', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Mix sugar and cocoa, stir to a smooth paste with the boiling water. Heat over the direct flame and then cook in a double boiler for about 30 minutes, or until a thick paste is formed. Chill.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Whip cream. Fold in cocoa paste, scald milk in double boiler or pan, add vanilla and salt. When serving hot chocolate, put chocolate mixture in a bowl and hot milk in a pitcher. Put a large spoonful of chocolate mixture in cup: add hot milk. Be sure milk is scalding hot; otherwise beverage will be lukewarm because of the cold paste that is added. I put sugar with my whipping cream when I whip it and some vanilla too.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

title: Dandelion Wine
author: Ann Fabric
summary: This recipe was a recipe of Grandma Anna Brunkhorst, submitted by granddaughter, Ann Fabric, daughter of Della Wintakger.Note received by Vivian Shane, daughter of Della and sister to Ann: I used to stay during high school years with Grandma Brunkhorst in her home in Lamont, Iowa. This was only on nights when I had special practice. At our evening meal, Grandma served me a small glass of her homemade dandelion wine. Since I was a teenager and had not drank wine I was very frustrated as to whether I should drink it or not. Finally, I rationalized Anna was my mother's mother so she wouldn't serve me anything I shouldn't have. I drank the wine!
ingredients: [{'amount': '4', 'unit': 'gallons', 'name': 'dandelion flowers', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': 'gallons', 'name': 'water', 'notes': 'boiling', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': 'lb', 'name': 'honey', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': '', 'name': 'lemons', 'notes': 'sliced', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': '', 'name': 'oranges', 'notes': 'sliced', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '12', 'unit': '', 'name': 'whole cloves', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': 'tbsp', 'name': 'yeast', 'notes': '2 packages', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'water', 'notes': 'warm', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Remove any stems from the flowers. Put the flowers in a large, warm crock and pour the boiling water over them. Let stand for a week.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Strain, squeezing all the juice out of the flowers; then discard. Add the slices of lemon, orange, and the cloves; stir well. Add the yeast which has been softened in the warm water. Let stand, covered for another 2 weeks.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Strain again and pour into wine bottles. Let the bottles stand uncorked for 5 days. Cork or cap bottles. Let wine develop for at least 2 months.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

author: Kathy Klotz
ingredients: [{'name': 'Cinnamon Chips:', 'type': 'group'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': '7-inch', 'name': 'flour tortillas', 'notes': '(I usually make more, they keep well)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'tbsp', 'name': 'sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tbsp', 'name': 'ground cinnamon', 'notes': '(or your own cinnamon and sugar mixture)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'name': 'Salsa:', 'type': 'group'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': '', 'name': 'medium Granny Smith apples', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'strawberries', 'notes': 'chopped (I used quick frozen)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': '', 'name': 'kiwi fruit (peeled', 'notes': 'chopped)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': 'small orange', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': 'tbsp', 'name': 'brown sugar', 'notes': 'packed', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': 'tbsp', 'name': 'orange marmalade', 'notes': 'apricot preserves, or apple jelly', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'name': 'Cinnamon Chips', 'type': 'group'}, {'text': '

Preheat the oven to 400° degrees. For cinnamon chips, lightly spray tortillas with water or Pam spray. Combine sugar and cinnamon in flour/sugar shaker; sprinkle over tortillas. Cut each tortilla into 8 wedges; place in a single layer on round baking stone.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake for 8-10 minutes or until lightly browned and crisp. Remove to cooling rack; cool completely.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'name': 'Salsa', 'type': 'group'}, {'text': '

For salsa, peel, core, and slice apples. Cut apples into quarters; chop with a food chopper. Slice or dice strawberries and chop kiwi. Place fruit in a 1-quart bowl.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Zest orange and juice until you have about 2 (tbsp) of juice. Add orange zest, orange juice, brown sugar and jelly to the fruit mixture; mix gently.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Refrigerate until ready to serve. Serve with cinnamon chips.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

instructions:
[{'text': '

Mix together cream cheese, ½ (cup) sugar, egg yolk and vanilla. Roll bread slices, with crust removed, flat with a rolling pin. Spread bread with cream cheese mixture. Roll up as for a jelly roll. Refrigerate overnight.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Cut rolls in half crosswise. Mix ¾ (cup) sugar and 2 (tsp) cinnamon.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Dip rolls in melted margarine and then roll in cinnamon-sugar mixture.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake on greased cookie sheets for 20-25 minutes at 350°.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Heat oven to 375°.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Combine sugar, flour and cinnamon. Separate dough into 16 triangles.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Dip 1 marshmallow in margarine; roll in sugar mixture. Place marshmallow on the wide end of the triangle and roll to the opposite point. Completely cover marshmallow with dough; firmly pinch edges to seal.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Dip 1 end in remaining margarine; place margarine-side down in an ungreased large muffin cup. Repeat with remaining marshmallows.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake 12-15 minutes until golden brown.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Boil potatoes in salted water. Drain potatoes and save water.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Add ¼ (cup) flour, ¼ (cup) white sugar and dry yeast to 1 (cup) potato water. Mix well and set aside to rise.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Mix mashed potatoes, the rest of the sugar, butter, milk, eggs, 1 (cup) flour and salt. Add raised yeast mixture.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Add 4-6 cups flour until dough is not sticky. Knead dough and cover to let rise in a warm spot.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Roll out dough to ½ inch thick.Spread with melted butter, cinnamon and brown sugar. Roll up and cut every 2 inches.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Put into a greased pan to let rise again.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake for 25 minutes at 350°. Frost when cooled.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

instructions:
[{'text': '

Dissolve yeast in lukewarm water. Add salt, sugar, melted margarine, and 2 eggs. Beat well with an electric mixer. Add flour gradually.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Knead well. Let rise until it doubles in size. Shape into rolls or make cinnamon rolls.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Mix brown sugar and cream in the bottom of a 9x13-inch ungreased pan.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Place rolls on top of the mixture. Bake at 350° for 30-35 minutes.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

title: Kolache
author: Pat Schumacher
ingredients: [{'amount': '', 'unit': '', 'name': 'Yeast Dough', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': 'cups', 'name': 'milk', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': 'stick margarine', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'lukewarm water', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': 'packages', 'name': 'yeast', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': '', 'name': '- ¾ (cup) sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'salt', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Scald milk; take from heat and add margarine. Set aside until lukewarm.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Meanwhile, add yeast to lukewarm water; set aside.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

When the milk mixture is lukewarm, add ½ - ¾ (cup) sugar and salt, yeast mixture and several cups of flour (about 3).

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Using a large mixing spoon, beat together well. Add enough flour to make dough stiff enough to knead. Try not to get it too stiff. Knead on pastry cloth or floured board. Let rise in a warm room until double in bulk. Knead down and make into hamburger buns - about 12 or 15 on a large cookie sheet or jelly roll pan. I usually make 12 on a pan. Be sure to flatten them as much as possible before they start to rise.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Let rise until light; gently, with a forefinger, press the centers down, hole about the size of a quarter.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Put about a teaspoon of your favorite jam in the center (apricot jam with a little lemon juice in it is good); can also use ½ cooked prunes or pureed apricots.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': "

Bake in a moderate oven until light brown. Take out of the oven and while hot, frost with a powdered sugar frosting made with lemon juice and butter or margarine. Frosting shouldn't be too thick and it will melt over the rolls like a glaze.

", 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

title: German Coffeecake (deutsch Kaffee Kuchen)
author: Bob and Kris Brunkhorst
ingredients: [{'amount': '2', 'unit': 'cups', 'name': 'milk (heated', 'notes': 'lukewarm)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '5', 'unit': '', 'name': 'level (tsp) yeast (1 pkg. = 4 (tsp)', 'notes': 'I use rapid rise)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '⅓', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¼', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'oil', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': '', 'name': 'eggs', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': 'tbsp', 'name': 'cinnamon', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'nutmeg', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'cloves', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '5½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'flour (may need ¼ (cup) more)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'dates', 'notes': 'prunes or raisins will do (diced)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'walnuts or pecans (optional)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

In a large bowl, KitchenAid or bread maker, put yeast and add warm milk. Add sugar, oil, spices, some of the flour, prunes or dates and then eggs. Knead for 5 minutes, dough should not be sticky.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Put in a greased bowl and turn to coat. Let rise, covered, in a warm place until double; 1 hour for regular yeast, ½ hour for rapid rise.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Punch dough down. Roll into 2 large loafs for coffeecake or 1 large and 3 small ones. Can shape them or "U" shape them or put them in a circle.Let rise again for 25 minutes.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': "

Put the oven at 250° and put them in; after about 10 minutes, turn the temperature up to 325° and bake for about 20 minutes for large. Don't let the bottom get too brown.

", 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Cool and then ice with powdered sugar frosting; dust lightly with cinnamon. Serve warm!

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

instructions:
[{'text': '

Heat oven to 350°. Line with paper baking cups 36 muffin cups.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Combine dry ingredients. Add apples, carrots, coconut, raisins and nuts. Mix well.

ingredients: [{'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': 'can Pillsbury crescent dinner rolls', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': 'egg (beaten)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': 'can evaporated milk', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'salt', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'Worcestershire sauce', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'Swiss cheese', 'notes': 'shredded', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '3½ oz can', 'name': 'French fried onions', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '9', 'unit': '', 'name': 'slices bacon (fried crisp', 'notes': 'crumbled)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': '', 'name': 'eggs (per person)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '', 'unit': '', 'name': 'Quart size zip lock freezer bags', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '', 'unit': '', 'name': 'Variety of ingredients (mushrooms', 'notes': 'onions, green pepper, cheeses, tomatoes, olives, ham, prepared sausage, etc.)', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Unroll and separate dough into triangles. Place in a 9-inch pie pan or 9-inch quiche pan, pressing pieces together to form a crust.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Combine egg, milk, salt and Worcestershire sauce. Stir in cheese. Sprinkle half of the onions over the unbaked crust.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Pour egg mixture into the crust. Sprinkle with bacon and onions.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake at 325° for 25-50 minutes (40-45 for quiche pan). Allow to cool 5 minutes before serving. Enjoy!

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Have everyone write their name on a quart-size zip lock freezer bag with a

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

permanent marker.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Crack 2 eggs into the bag, no more than 2 eggs in each bag. Shake to combine them. Put in chosen ingredients and shake. Make sure to get all the air out of the bag and zip it up.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

title: Great Grandma Dell's Angel Food Cake
author: Alexandra Matloff
summary:
The most delicious angel food cake I have ever tasted has been handed down in my family for four generations. I call it my "Great Grandma Dell's Angel FoodCake." My great grandma Della learned to make this special angel food cake from her mother, my great-great grandma Anna, who lived in Austria. My great grandma Della loved to prepare and eat this tasty cake. Great Grandma Della was raised in a small farming town in Masonville, Iowa. She had fresh eggs from the chickens and milk from the cows that she raised on her farm. The angel food cake recipe is a favorite of mine because when I make the cake with my Grandma, she shares stories about the times when she and her mother used to make this recipe. I like to watch my Grandma crack open the twelve eggs for the cake. Sometimes she lets me crack them. The cake is used mainly on birthdays. I love the smell of the cake cooking. It reminds me of all the happy birthdays we have celebrated. I like the fluffy cake with chocolate ice cream.

This recipe and story was written by Annamae Fabric's granddaughter, Alexandra Matloff, daughter of Natalie Fabric Matloff, as an English project, November 1999.
ingredients: [{'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'cake flour (sifted)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¾', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'fine sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'egg whites (approximately 12 eggs)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'cream of tartar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¼', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'salt', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'vanilla flavoring', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '12¼', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'almond flavoring', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¾', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'fine sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

This mouth-watering angel food cake is made by first, combining the sifted flour with ¾ (cup) sugar and sifting four times. Then, while the oven is preheating at 375", beat together the egg whites, cream of tartar, salt and flavorings until soft peaks form.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Next, add the remaining ¾ (cup) of sugar, 2 (tbsp) at a time, beating the mixture after each addition of sugar. The flour and sugar combination is then folded in very, very gently and carefully. After pouring the mixture into an ungreased 10-inch tube pan, the mixture is baked at 375° for 35-40 minutes.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Finally, remove the cake and turn it upside down in the pan onto a large Coke bottle. In about 1½ hours, the cake will be cool. The cake is removed from the pan by running a sharp knife along the sides. Now you are ready to enjoy the most wonderful and sweetest dessert this side of heaven.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

title: Cherry Winks
author: Ann and Philip Brunkhorst
summary: Yield: about 5 dozen, 2-inch diameter cookies.
ingredients: [{'amount': '5', 'unit': 'cups', 'name': 'corn flakes', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2¼', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'flour (sifted)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'baking powder', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'vanilla', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'nuts (chopped', 'notes': 'optional)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '⅓', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'cherries (finely cut)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'dates (pitted', 'notes': 'finely cut)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '15', 'unit': '', 'name': 'maraschino cherries (cut in quarters)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '2', 'unit': '', 'name': 'eggs', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'soda', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'salt', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¾', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'butter (softened)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Crush corn flakes into coarse crumbs. Set aside.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Sift together flour, baking powder, soda and salt. Set aside.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Put butter and sugar into a large mixing bowl; beat until light and fluffy. Add eggs and vanilla; beat well.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Add sifted dry ingredients; mix until combined. Stir in nuts, dates and cherries.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Roll into balls; then roll in crushed corn flakes. Place on ungreased baking sheets; top each cookie with a cherry quarter.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake at 375° for about 12 minutes or until lightly browned. Remove immediately from pans; cool on wire racks.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

instructions:
[{'text': '

Mix butter and sugar. When creamy, beat in milk and vanilla. Stir in flour, mixing well. Add cherries and nuts.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

title: Pumpkin Pecan Tassies
author: Ann and Phil Brunkhorst
summary: Yield: 2 dozen.
ingredients: [{'name': 'Crust', 'type': 'group'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'butter (no substitutes', 'notes': 'softened)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '3 oz package', 'name': 'cream cheese (softened)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'all-purpose flour', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'name': 'Filling', 'type': 'group'}, {'amount': '¾', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'brown sugar (packed', 'notes': 'divided)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¼', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'pumpkin (cooked or canned)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'plus 1 (tbsp) butter (melted', 'notes': 'divided)', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': 'egg yolk', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'tbsp', 'name': 'Half-and-Half', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'vanilla extract', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¼', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'rum extract (optional) ⅛ (tsp) ground cinnamon', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '⅛', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'ground nutmeg', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'pecans', 'notes': 'chopped', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

In a small mixing bowl, cream butter and cream cheese. Beat in flour. Shape into 24 balls.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

With floured fingers, press onto the bottom and up the sides of greased miniature muffin cups.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake at 325° for 8-10 minutes or until edges are lightly browned.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Meanwhile, in a bowl, combine ½ (cup) brown sugar, pumpkin, 4 (tsp) butter, egg yolk, cream, extracts, cinnamon and nutmeg. Spoon into warm cups. Combine the pecans and remaining brown sugar and butter; sprinkle over filling.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Bake for 23-27 minutes longer or until set and edges are golden brown.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Cool for 10 minutes before removing from pans to wire racks.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

instructions:
[{'text': '

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Beat butter in a large mixer bowl until creamy. Beat in flour, sugar and salt until crumbly.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

With floured fingers, press 1¾ (cup) flour mixture onto bottom of prepared baking pan; reserve

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

remaining mixture.

Bake for 10-12 minutes or until the edges are golden brown.

instructions:
[{'name': 'Crust And Filling', 'type': 'group'}, {'text': '

Heat oven to 325°. In a medium bowl, combine crust ingredients. Mix well and press into the bottom and 1 inch up on sides of an ungreased 10-inch springform pan.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Beat cream cheese in a large bowl until smooth. Add eggs, 1 at a time, beating well after each addition.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Add sugar and almond extract; beat until smooth. Add ½ (cup) whipping cream. Blend well.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Spoon 3½ (cup) cream mixture into crust. Spread evenly. Carefully spoon 1 (cup) pie filling over cream cheese mixture. (Reserve the rest of the pie filling for garnish.) Spoon remaining cream cheese mixture evenly over pie filling.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

APRICOT GLAZED TURKEY BREAST

(lb)) 1 (tbsp) honey

½ (cup) apricot jam 1 /2 (tsp) salt

¼ (cup) fresh orange juice ½(tsp) pepper

Remove skin from turkey breast. Combine remaining ingredients until well blended. Spray roasting pan with cooking spray. Place the turkey breast bone-

side down and cover the top with half the sauce. Bake 10 minutes at 450. Reduce temperature to 350° and bake 40 minutes. Remove foil and spread with remaining glaze. Insert meat thermometer in the thickest part of the breast and

bake, uncovered, until the turkey reaches 165 to 170 (about 40-50 minutes

more). Baste with glaze often. Let stand for about 5 minutes before slicing.

HAM BALLS Katie Weigel

Combine ham loaf mix, hamburger, graham cracker crumbs, eggs and milk. Mix and shape into balls. Mix together vinegar, soup, brown sugar and dry mustard.

Pour over the balls. Bake at 325 for easily towards the end.

ZESTY GRILLED HAM

Pat Schumacher and Family

In a small saucepan, bring brown sugar, horseradish and lemon juice to a boil. Brush over both sides of ham. Grill over medium-hot heat, turning once, until heated through and well glazed, about 20-25 minutes. Yields: 4 servings.

SCALLOPED POTATOES AND HAM

sliced, about 2 (lb)) Salt and pepper

Katie and Mark Weigel

Place ½ the ham into a 2-quart casserole. Cover with half the potatoes and half the onion. Sift half the flour over; season with salt and pepper. Repeat layers ending with flour on top. Pour milk over all.

Bake, uncovered, in a 350° oven for 1-1¼ hours or until potatoes are nearly tender. Uncover. Drizzle with melted butter. Bake an additional 15 minutes or until done.

HASH BROWNS AND HAM

Combine corn flakes and melted butter and sprinkle over potatoes. Sprinkle mozzarella on top and bake for 10-15 minutes longer.

Spread both sides of meat with a light layer of mustard. Dredge in flour. Brown in skillet with a little oil. Place meat in roasting pan. Spoon rice soup over meat; then add ½ can water to skillet to get all browning from pan. Pour over chops. Cover with foil. Bake until tender. Serve with more rice. Use juice on meat as gravy.

SWISS STEAK Patricia Maas

Combine flour, salt and pepper in a plastic bag. Pound meat with the flour mixture. Brown meat with shortening on both sides. Place in roasting pan with chopped onions, tomatoes and juice. Cook 1½ hours at 350° . You can thicken juice for gravy. Serves 8.

B.B.Q. BEEF

Ann and Phil Brunkhorst

Mix together onion salt, salt, garlic salt, celery salt and Worcestershire sauce. Rub onto both sides of meat. Bake in a pan at 225 for 8 hours. Pour off part of liquid and cool. Slice meat thinly or shred. Put back in pan.

Combine sugar, salad dressing and BBQ sauce. Combine sauce with liquid and pour over meat. Return to oven and heat through at 300 -325. Best if made the day before serving.

SALISBURY STEAK Angie Brunkhorst

Combine ground beef, bread crumbs, egg, salt, pepper, onion and celery and shape into oval patties, about 1-inch thick. Using a small amount of butter, brown on both sides in skillet.

Albert Brunkhorst was known to ride his horse to the farm

from Lamont, approximately 5 miles daily

until shortly before his death on November 21, 1935.

SWISS STEAK Mary Lisa Goetschel

Using a meat hammer, pound flour into both sides until absorbed. Saut‚ meat, brown on both sides. Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Spread onion, celery and green pepper over steak. Add chili sauce mixed with water. Cover and bake in a 300 oven for 2-2½ hours or at 325 for 1½ hours. Drippings can be thickened for gravy. Serves 6.

HUNGARIAN GOULASH Marlene Goetschel

Brown meat. Add remaining ingredients. Cover and simmer about 3 hours or until meat is tender. Remove bay leaf. Serves 6.

I make this a day early and serve over noodles or potatoes. Great for a quick warm up dinner if you are having guests.

Anna Brunkhorst suffered a stroke in 1951 and was never able to speak afterwards. She died on January 18, 1955.

CHILI CON CARNE

In Memory of My Mom, Mae Brunkhorst

Patricia Maas

Salt and pepper (to taste) Macaroni

Brown hamburger and diced onion. Cook until done. Add home canned tomatoes. Heat. Add cooked macaroni. Season to taste.

We kids enjoyed this recipe. it contains no beans, but we called it Chili Con Came.

Mix potatoes, cream cheese, ½ cup of the shredded cheese and garlic until well blended. Put potato mixture on top of meat. Sprinkle the remaining ½ (cup) shredded cheese on top. Bake for 20 minutes or until heated through.

¼(tsp) pepper 1 (cup) mushrooms

Rice, vermicelli or Chinese noodles

Cut meat cross grain in paper thin slices. Combine the soy sauce, broth, sugar, pepper and Accent. Brown the meat and pour soy sauce mixture with rest of ingredients over the meat. Serve on rice or vermicelli noodles (very thin noodles).

Barbara Thurn Brunkhorst's father, Franz (Frank) returned to Europe

to visit and failed to return. His wife had to go to Europe

to get him to return.

Albert also wished to return to Germany to visit, but his wife, Anna,

was afraid that he too, would not wish to return

so he never did return to his birth country.

TORTILLA SPIRALS

½ (cup) black olives (pitted, minced)

Karen Eichmann

Cayenne pepper (to taste) 12-14 (10-inch) tortillas

Mix all the ingredients in a food processor. Spread about 3-4 (tbsp) of the mixture on top of one tortilla. Roll up like a jelly roll; wrap in plastic wrap and refrigerate or freeze. Repeat with remaining mixture.

When you're ready to serve, slice the rolls into ¼?inch slices. Bake the spirals on a lightly greased baking pan at 400° for 12-15 minutes. This makes a huge batch...so you can just bake what you need and leave the remaining rolled up tortillas frozen until the next hungry bunch comes over.

cream of chicken soup

Reserve the soup juice for gravy. Mix all ingredients, except cream of mushroom or cream of chicken soup. Shape into balls. Brown. Place browned meatballs into a roaster and add pan drippings and soup juice. Mix 1 can cream

soup with ½ can water. Pour over meatballs. Bake in a 350° oven for 45

minutes, covered, and 15 minutes, uncovered. Great served with mashed

potatoes or noodles.

PRIZE-WINNING MEATLOAF Monica Piers all

Combine all meatloaf ingredients thoroughly. Pack firmly into an ungreased 8½ x4½ x2½?inch loaf pan. Bake 1 hour 15 minutes at 350° . Let stand 5 minutes before slicing.

Note: Can top meatloaf with one of the optional toppings.

MEATLOAF Stefanie Brunkhorst

¾ (cup) milk (can use evaporated) 114C. ketchup

TOPPING:

½ (cup) ketchup 2 (tbsp) brown sugar

½(tsp) dry mustard

Combine meatloaf ingredients. Place into a loaf pan. Bake at 350° for 1 hour or more. Combine topping ingredients. Spread topping on top of meatloaf halfway through baking.

MEATLOAF CASSEROLE

Favorite meatloaf recipe (prepared, set 1 (tsp) salt

Ann and Philip Brunkhorst

M

E

Place meatloaf mixture over top of potatoes. Frost meatloaf with ketchup,

mustard and brown sugar if desired. Bake in a 350° oven until done. Recipe

may be doubled and placed into a 9x13-inch pan but needs to be baked longer.

CREAMY FETTUCCINE ALFREDO

¾ (cup) Parmesan cheese, grated 8 oz fettuccine (cooked, drained) ½ (cup) margarine

Combine all ingredients, except fettuccine. Simmer over low heat until smooth, stirring constantly. Pour over fettuccine, toss lightly. May thin with a little milk if fettuccine seems too thick. May add sliced cooked chicken breast or cooked shrimp if desired.

title: Sawdust Pie
author: Katie Weigel
summary:
CRANBERRY RELISH-

THANKSGIVING

RECIPE

In Memory of My Mom, Mae Brunkhorst

By Patricia Maas

Pick over fresh cranberries. Grind cranberries in old fashion grinder. Wash orange; cut into quarters and grind in grinder. Mix ground cranberries and ground orange. Add sugar to taste. May be frozen.

We kids ground the cranberries and orange at Thanksgiving.

BEAN SALAD-THANKSGIVING RECIPE Patricia Maas

In a saucepan, combine vinegar, water and sugar. Bring to a boil and then simmer 3 minutes. Cool slightly. Pour vinegar mixture over bean mixture and refrigerate 24 hours.

On July 11, 2002 the Century Farm home burnt. It was replaced with a

manufactured home from Design Homes, Prairie du Chien, WI.

Philip and Ann Brunkhorst took residence

in their new home in the spring of 2005.

BROCCOLI-APPLE SALAD ? Patricia Maas

THANKSGIVING RECIPE

chopped)

Mix dressing ingredients and refrigerate overnight. Combine dressing with vegetables and apples just before serving.

BROCCOLI CAULIFLOWER SALAD Monica Piersall

In a large bowl, mix together cauliflower, broccoli, onion and carrots. Add mozzarella or cheddar cheese, Parmesan cheese and crumbled bacon. Combine mayonnaise, sugar and vinegar; add dressing to your salad. Best when chilled several hours or overnight.

/-þ

CUCUMBERS IN CREAM SAUCE Edna Brunkhorst

½ (cup) sugar 6-7 cucumbers (depending on size) ⅓ (cup) vinegar

Clean and slice cucumbers and onion. Combine all ingredients and mix. Will last several weeks.

S

A

A

D

BROCCOLI SALAD

Ann and Phil Brunkhorst

¾ (cup) slivered almonds

Combine salad ingredients in a bowl. Combine dressing ingredients and pour over salad 1 hour before serving and chill.

LAYERED LETTUCE SALAD Angie Brunkhorst

(thawed)

Layer vegetables in a 9x13-inch glass pan. Cover with mayonnaise, sealing against edges of pan. Sprinkle with sugar. Cover with grated cheddar cheese and bacon bits. Cover tightly and let stand overnight.

Variation: May add 3 hard boiled, sliced eggs.

CUCUMBERS IN SOUR CREAM Elizabeth Lockhart

Peel cucumbers and cut into very thin slices. Whisk together sour cream and the next 4 ingredients in a large bowl; stir in cucumbers. Serve immediately. 4-6 servings.

SLICED CUCUMBERS (FOR TABLE USE) Katie Weigel

¼ (tsp) celery seeds Cucumbers A

D

Peel and slice cucumbers. Soak in salt water; drain. Add above ingredients. Refrigerate; let marinate. Serve.

DELUXE GERMAN POTATO LaVerne and Pat Schumacher

SALAD

C. vinegar 2 (tbsp) fresh parsley, chopped

½ (cup) water Additional salt (to taste)

In a skillet, cook bacon until crisp. Drain, reserving ¼ (cup) drippings. Crumble bacon and set aside. Saut‚ the celery and onion in drippings until tender. Combine sugar and flour; add to skillet with vinegar, water, salt and mustard. Cook, stirring constantly, until mixture thickens and bubbles.

In a large bowl, combine potatoes, carrots and parsley; pour the sauce over and stir gently to coat. Season to taste with additional salt. Spoon into a serving dish; garnish with the crumbled bacon. Serve warm. Yield: 14-16 servings.

Philip, Jennifer, Angie, Katie, Alicia, Stefani received the Century Farm award at the Iowa State Fair in August 1987.

Also present were Ann Brunkhorst, Patricia Maas

and Jim and Monica Piersall.

POTATO SALAD Katie Weigel

Boil eggs. Boil potatoes with skins on. Can leave them in the refrigerator to cool for a couple of days. Peel eggs and potatoes. I grate the eggs and potatoes, but you can just dice them. Mix all ingredients and refrigerate.

PASTA SALAD

(drained)

Mix all together. Refrigerate. Serve.

PASTA SALAD

Elizabeth Lockhart

⅔ (cup) Italian dressing

Monice Piersall

Mix together. Refrigerate. Keeps up to 2 weeks.

ingredients: [{'amount': '½', 'unit': '', 'name': 'medium onion', 'notes': 'chopped', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': '', 'name': 'stick butter', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'salt', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '½', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'pepper', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'Half-and-Half cream', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '12 oz package', 'name': 'frozen hash browns (thawed)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'Parmesan cheese (divided)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '', 'unit': '', 'name': 'Paprika', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Heat oven to 350° degrees. Saute onion in butter. Add salt, pepper and cream; heat. Add hash browns and cook while stirring until cream thickens. Add half of the Parmesan cheese, stir well.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Pour into a greased 11x7-inch pan. Cover with foil and bake for 40 minutes. Remove foil and top with remaining cheese. Sprinkle with paprika. Broil to melt cheese.

title: Canned Beef
author: Ann and Philip Brunkhorst
summary: I have canned chicken breast and pork loin using this method also. Awesome heated and served over cooked noodles or with mashed potatoes.
instructions:
[{'text': '

Prepare canning jars by sterilizing canning jars. I prefer using wide mouth jars. Place ½ (tsp) salt per pint or 1 (tsp) salt per quart. Use only canning salt as table salt will leave a cloudiness in the bottom of the jar.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Remove bone, gristle and most of the fat from the meat. (I use chuck roast.) Cut tender meat into chunks 1 or 2 inches thick which can be packed into canning jars. Pack tightly into jars making sure that all air bubbles are removed. Leave 1 inch headspace at top of jar. Wipe mouth of jar. Adjust jar lids.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Process at 10 (lb) of pressure in pressure. Pints for 75 minutes and quarts for 90 minutes. Follow canner instructions for removal.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

ingredients: [{'amount': '20', 'unit': 'cups', 'name': 'fresh sweet corn (cut from cob)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '', 'unit': '', 'name': 'Small handful salt', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '3', 'unit': '', 'name': 'sticks butter or margarine', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': '', 'name': '½ (cups) water', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Transfer to another container and immerse the container into ice water. When corn is cool, bag

in 1-qt. freezer bags. Put 2 (cups) into each bag.

title: Brined Cabbage Or Mild Sauerkraut
author: Ann Fabric
summary: This amount of cabbage will pack into a 2-qt. jar, which will help you figure out how many jars of kraut you wish to make. This recipe was used by Della Brunkhorst Wintakger and her mother Anna Brunkhorst.
ingredients: [{'amount': '8', 'unit': 'tsp', 'name': 'salt', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': 'lb', 'name': 'cabbage (prepared)', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Mix the shredded cabbage very carefully with the salt. Pack into sterilized 2-qt. jars. Press down the cabbage until the juice runs out and covers it. If the juice does not cover, add a weak brine made by adding 1 (tbsp) of salt to 2 (cups) of water. Hold the cabbage down under the brine by slipping 2 strips of wood, crosswise in the jar below the neck. Wipe off the top of the jar with a clean damp cloth. Place a rubber ring on top. Screw down top until it catches and no more.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Set jars on an enamel tray to catch the juice that will leak out during fermentation. Let stand until fermentation ceases, which will be about 10 days. The bubbling will stop when the fermentation is over. If, at this time, the juice does not cover the cabbage, add more brine to the jar.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

This will keep for several weeks if transferred to a cold place. If you wish to keep it longer, the jars will have to be processed for 30 minutes in a boiling water bath.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

For best results you should use pure granulated salt, which is called bag salt or dairy salt. Do not use table or rock salt.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': "

If you haven't an enamel tray be sure and use old pans or trays so that it won't matter if they become rusty.

", 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': "

For good results, use a thermometer to test the surrounding temperature and don't guess at it. Temperatures are carefully held where kraut is made on a large scale for canning.

", 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

And don\'t guess at the amount of salt, or "think" you have 4 (lb) of shredded cabbage; actually weigh it.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

title: Strawberry Freezer Jam
author: Ann and Philip Brunkhorst
summary: Yields: 5 (1-cup) containers.
ingredients: [{'amount': '2', 'unit': 'cups', 'name': 'strawberries', 'notes': 'crushed, use fully ripe fruit', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '4', 'unit': 'cups', 'name': 'sugar', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '¾', 'unit': 'cup', 'name': 'water', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}, {'amount': '1', 'unit': 'box', 'name': 'Sure Jell Fruit Pectin', 'notes': '', 'type': 'ingredient'}]
instructions:
[{'text': '

Rinse clean containers and lids in boiling water. Dry thoroughly. Wash, stem

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

and crush strawberries. Measure 2 (cups) fruit into a bowl. Stir in sugar. Let stand 10 minutes, stirring occasionally.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Mix water and pectin in a small saucepan. Bring to a boil on high heat, stirring constantly. Continue, boiling and stirring 1 minute. Add to the fruit mixture; stir 3 minutes or until sugar is dissolved and no longer grainy. (A few sugar crystals may remain.)

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}, {'text': '

Fill containers immediately to within ½ ?inch of tops. Wipe edges of containers; immediately cover with lids. Let stand at room temperature for 24 hours. Jam is now ready to use. Store in the refrigerator up to 3 weeks or freeze.

', 'type': 'instruction', 'image_url': ''}]

title: Peeling Kiwi Fruit
author: None
summary:
There is a quick and simple way to peel kiwi fruit with a teaspoon. This method works best with fruit that is ripe but not too soft. First cut off both ends of a kiwi. Then slip a teaspoon just under the skin, matching the spoon's curve to the curve of the fruit. Now slide the spoon around the kiwi to separate the fruit from the skin, being careful not to dig into the flesh. Once the spoon has been completely run around the fruit, it will easily slip out of the skin in one smooth

piece!
